{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17095"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17095"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.84,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9785"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62859"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5064"},{"type":"tags","id":"5095"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23182"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman with type 2 diabetes mellitus has poor glycaemic control despite maximum doses of metformin. Her glycated haemoglobin is 75 mmol/mol (20-42). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer doctor recommends adding a sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT2) inhibitor to her treatment regimen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of SGLT2 inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces glucose absorption from the small intestine","Decreases glucagon secretion from pancreatic alpha cells","Blocks glucose reabsorption in the proximal renal tubule","Enhances insulin sensitivity in skeletal muscle","Increases insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESGLT2 inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking glucose reabsorption in the proximal renal tubule\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to increased urinary glucose excretion and subsequent reduction in blood glucose levels. The mechanism is insulin-independent, making these medications effective at any stage of type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces glucose absorption from the small intestine\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of alpha-glucosidase inhibitors, which act in the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases glucagon secretion from pancreatic alpha cells\u003C/strong\u003E describes one of the mechanisms of glucagon-like peptide-1 receptor agonists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances insulin sensitivity in skeletal muscle\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of metformin and thiazolidinediones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of sulfonylureas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased urinary glucose excretion also results in osmotic diuresis and caloric loss, contributing to the beneficial effects of weight loss and blood pressure reduction seen with these medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT2) inhibitors reduce blood glucose by blocking glucose reabsorption in the proximal renal tubule.","SGLT2 inhibition leads to increased urinary glucose excretion and osmotic diuresis.","SGLT2 inhibitors work independently of insulin."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62859"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17095"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62859"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T17:28:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T17:29:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9785"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun